### Inheritence 
--> where a one class(Called the subclass or childClass) inherits form Parent class
--> Inheritence is a often termed "Is-A" relationship 
--> it can achieved by in java use of extends keyword.

==> A super class (or Parent Class) whose the Properties are inherited.
--> A sub class(or child class) is the class that inherits those properties.

*** Types of Inheritence
1. Single Inheritence
 --> where a child class inherits properties and behaviours from another class.
    ----Code----
 class Person 
{
   int age;
   String name;
   void display()
    {
        System.out.println("saurav");
    }
}
class Students extends Person
{
    int rollNumber;
}
public class Main {
     public static void main(String[] args)
        {
           Students s1 = new Students();
           s1.name = "saurav";
           s1.age = 20;
           s1.rollNumber = 23;
           System.out.println(s1.name);
           System.out.println(s1.age);
           System.out.println(s1.rollNumber);
          s1.display();
      }
}

2. ---------Multi-level Inheritence---------
--> mukti-level inheritence is when a class which itself inherit from another class. it's form a chain of inheritence
chain:-> parent->child->GrandChild.
**Code**
class Program1 {
void display()
{
System.out.println("Inside a Program1");
}
}
public class Program2 extends Program1 {
    void display2(){
System.out.println("Inside display 2");
   }
 }
public class Program3 extends Program2 {
void display3()
{
   System.out.println("Inside dispaly2");
}
}
public class Main {
   public static void main(String[] args)
   {
      Program3 p3 = new Program3();
      p3.display();
      p3.display2();
      p3.display3();
   }
}

--> Output
Inside a Program1
Inside display 2
Inside dispaly2

-------------******---------------
3. -------------Herarichial inheritence--------------
      --> Is a type of inheritence where two or more classes inherit from the same base classes
KEY Points:-> one Parent class but two child class.
                 Program
                 /     \
             Student   Child1
***Code***
class Program {
    void disp1()
   {
      System.out.println("Inside a Program class");
   }
}
  class Student extends Program {
      void disp2()
   {
      System.out.println("Inside a Student class");
   } 
}
  class Child1 extends Program {
       void disp3()
   {
      System.out.println("Inside a child1 class");
   } 
}
 public class Main {
     public static void main(String[] args) {
          Child1 ch = new Child1();
         ch.disp1();   // Parent method
        ch.disp3();   // Child1 method
        Student st = new Student();
        st.disp1();   // Parent method
        st.disp2();   // Student method
  }
}

------------------*****--------------------
###  Hybrid Inheritance
--> Hybrid inheritance is a combination of two or more types of inheritance (like single, multiple, hierarchical).
****Code****
            class A {
    void methodA() {
        System.out.println("Class A method");
    }
}
class B extends A {
    void methodB() {
        System.out.println("Class B method");
    }
}
interface C {
    void methodC();
}
class D extends B implements C {
    public void methodC() {
        System.out.println("Class C method");
    }
    void methodD() {
        System.out.println("Class D method");
    }
}
public class HybridInheritanceDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        D obj = new D();
        obj.methodA();  // from A
        obj.methodB();  // from B
        obj.methodC();  // from C
        obj.methodD();  // from D
    }
}
-------------------**********----------------
### Multiple Inheritence
--> Technically not allowed in java.
    --> beacause one child have two Problem? Ans => No, one child have only one Parents.
--> It's create a Ambiguity Problem.
--> This is technically called Diamond Problem.
-> Multiple Inheritence is not allowed in java Programming language.
--> but it is Possible to achived in Java Programming language with the help of interface.
***Diagram***
 Class A   Class B
    \        /
     \      /
      Class C   ‚ùå NOT ALLOWED

